Mr Pickles, the Local Government Secretary, said it was ‘a constitutional affront that Englishmen and women are being fined in arbitrary and unfair ways’ to fill their cash shortfalls.

Councils are on track to make £635million profit from parking this year – with income from fines and penalties alone topping £340million.

The latest criticism came in evidence to the Commons’ Transport Select Committee from the Traffic Penalty Tribunal, set up by ministers to consider drivers’ appeals against parking fines.

It cited concern over routine use of CCTV cameras to issue millions of fines. Department for Transport guidance says CCTV should only be used when it is impractical to use traffic wardens.

